<DOC><DOCNO> AP880504-0101 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0936EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-People-Redford     05-04 0262</FIRST><SECOND>PM-People-Redford,0273</SECOND><HEAD>Actor-Reford Goes To Soviet Union For Showings of His Films</HEAD><DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Actor-director Robert Redford is leavingfor the Soviet Union on Saturday for a 10-day trip to discuss twoof his favorite subjects, films and the environment.   Redford was invited last December by Elem Klimov, president ofthe Soviet Filmmakers Union. Seven of his films will be shown inLeningrad, Moscow and Tbilisi.   While in Moscow, the actor will co-host discussions on globalenvironment with the Soviet Academy of Sciences, the UniversityCorporation for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, Colo., and theNatural Resources Defense Council, N.Y.   The two-day meeting was initiated by the Institute for ResourceManagement, an organization created by Redford in 1981 thatattempts to find resolutions to environmental conflicts andcontroversies.   Soviet and American scientists and environmental-policy expertswill discuss cooperation on the global warming some scientistsbelieve is taking place due to ozone depletion in the upperatmosphere and the buildup of carbon dioxide.   ``I am honored to be invited at a critical crossroads in therelationship between our countries,'' said Redford.   Another workshop in Moscow will focus on Redford's SundanceInstitute for Film and Television in Utah, and on plans for anexchange between young American and Soviet filmmakers.   His films to be shown are ``All the President's Men,'' ``TheSting,'' ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' ``The Natural,''``Jeremiah Johnson,'' ``The Electric Horseman'' and his latestdirectorial effort ``The Milagro Beanfield War.''   The tour is supported by the U.S. Information Agency'sU.S.-Soviet Exchange Initiative and the American Embassy in Moscow.</TEXT></DOC>